The sum of the first $n$ terms of the geometric sequence $\left\{\frac{1}{4},\frac{1}{8},\frac{1}{16},\dots \right\}$ is equal to $\frac{1}{4}\cdot\frac{1-\left(\frac{1}{2}\right)^n}{1-\frac{1}{2}}= \frac{1}{2}\left(1-\left(\frac{1}{2}\right)^n\right)$. We are given that this sum is equal to $\frac{63}{128}$, so we can set up an equation and solve for $n$: \begin{align*}
\frac{1}{2}\left(1-\left(\frac{1}{2}\right)^n\right)&=\frac{63}{128}\\
\Rightarrow\qquad 1-\left(\frac{1}{2}\right)^n&=\frac{63}{64}\\
\Rightarrow\qquad \left(\frac{1}{2}\right)^n&=\frac{1}{64}\\
\Rightarrow\qquad n&=\boxed{6}
\end{align*}

